1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,070
In this demo, I'm going to show you how to read a few review text files in a folder.

2
00:00:04,070 --> 00:00:07,995
We're going to go ahead and read each file line by line to extract the title,

3
00:00:07,995 --> 00:00:09,855
URL, and text of each review.

4
00:00:09,855 --> 00:00:12,975
We're going to then store this information in a Pandas DataFrame.

5
00:00:12,975 --> 00:00:15,270
Now we have three Roger Ebert reviews

6
00:00:15,270 --> 00:00:17,490
programmatically downloaded and we're going to use them.

7
00:00:17,490 --> 00:00:19,035
They're in this directory here.

8
00:00:19,035 --> 00:00:23,805
Note how if we double-click into one txt file with each dot txt file,

9
00:00:23,805 --> 00:00:25,560
the first line is the title,

10
00:00:25,560 --> 00:00:27,645
the second line is the URL,

11
00:00:27,645 --> 00:00:30,915
and the third line and onwards is the review text.

12
00:00:30,915 --> 00:00:37,295
Let's get started. We'll start with importing Pandas' and Python built-in glob module,

13
00:00:37,295 --> 00:00:40,975
a library that helps with Unix style pathname pattern expansion.

14
00:00:40,975 --> 00:00:44,300
This essentially means that we can use glob patterns to specify

15
00:00:44,300 --> 00:00:47,750
sets of filenames using wildcard characters like asterisk,

16
00:00:47,750 --> 00:00:50,350
which can be used to patch a string of any length.

17
00:00:50,350 --> 00:00:51,920
It is a lot of information,

18
00:00:51,920 --> 00:00:55,280
but you only need to remember the glob.glob.

19
00:00:55,280 --> 00:00:58,120
The pattern ebert reviews 2017,

20
00:00:58,120 --> 00:01:01,985
slash asterisk dot txt will find any file within

21
00:01:01,985 --> 00:01:06,640
our reviews folder that has a dot txt extension regardless of the file's name.

22
00:01:06,640 --> 00:01:09,140
The asterisk is a wildcard character.

23
00:01:09,140 --> 00:01:11,690
It allows you to find and process all text files in

24
00:01:11,690 --> 00:01:15,145
the directory without specifying each filename individually.

25
00:01:15,145 --> 00:01:18,640
Now, let's go ahead and start our implementation.

26
00:01:18,640 --> 00:01:20,950
First, we're going to go ahead and create an empty list,

27
00:01:20,950 --> 00:01:24,400
text list to store information from each file in the directory.

28
00:01:24,400 --> 00:01:27,785
Now what we're going to do is iterate through files in our directory.

29
00:01:27,785 --> 00:01:30,070
We'll iterate through all the text files in

30
00:01:30,070 --> 00:01:33,415
our reviews directory using the glob.glob function.

31
00:01:33,415 --> 00:01:37,210
Next, we're going to go ahead and open the text file with

32
00:01:37,210 --> 00:01:41,815
open ebert review encoding equals UTFE as file.

33
00:01:41,815 --> 00:01:44,065
In Python 3, when opening texts to read,

34
00:01:44,065 --> 00:01:45,610
you should always use open with

35
00:01:45,610 --> 00:01:49,495
an encoding parameter to ensure that you get correctly decoded unicode,

36
00:01:49,495 --> 00:01:51,215
or an error message.

37
00:01:51,215 --> 00:01:54,460
Here we opened each text file using a path generated

38
00:01:54,460 --> 00:01:57,985
from glob and pass it into a file handle called file.

39
00:01:57,985 --> 00:02:02,255
Then we read the first line of the file, which is the title.

40
00:02:02,255 --> 00:02:06,250
Since text files are separated by new line characters and

41
00:02:06,250 --> 00:02:10,740
the file object returned from with open this file is an iterator,

42
00:02:10,740 --> 00:02:15,350
we can read the file line by line using file dot readline.

43
00:02:15,350 --> 00:02:17,095
In our text files,

44
00:02:17,095 --> 00:02:19,375
the title is followed by a bit of whitespace,

45
00:02:19,375 --> 00:02:22,990
which is actually the backslash end or the new line character.

46
00:02:22,990 --> 00:02:27,325
We can get rid of that by slicing it off at the end of the string using

47
00:02:27,325 --> 00:02:32,470
indexing by minus one which basically means keep everything but the last character.

48
00:02:32,470 --> 00:02:34,950
Now we've got the movie title.

49
00:02:34,950 --> 00:02:38,125
Next, we're going to go ahead and grab the URL,

50
00:02:38,125 --> 00:02:39,355
which is the second line.

51
00:02:39,355 --> 00:02:41,560
You're going to use dot readline

52
00:02:41,560 --> 00:02:46,565
again to catch the second line and remove that newline character at the end.

53
00:02:46,565 --> 00:02:49,075
Now, next with file dot read

54
00:02:49,075 --> 00:02:51,970
everything from the third line and onwards is the review text,

55
00:02:51,970 --> 00:02:55,565
so we can just read the rest of the file using the dot read function.

56
00:02:55,565 --> 00:02:58,570
Now, it's time to get this into a DataFrame.

57
00:02:58,570 --> 00:03:01,435
We add the title, review URL,

58
00:03:01,435 --> 00:03:03,955
and review text that we just read

59
00:03:03,955 --> 00:03:08,000
to a list of dictionaries and we give them proper names.

60
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:11,695
Next, what we're going to do is after iterating through all the files,

61
00:03:11,695 --> 00:03:13,855
convert our text list,

62
00:03:13,855 --> 00:03:18,430
or list of dictionaries into a Pandas DataFrame called df.

63
00:03:18,430 --> 00:03:20,455
Here, as you can see, we're specifically

64
00:03:20,455 --> 00:03:23,035
denoting the column names in the order of title,

65
00:03:23,035 --> 00:03:25,310
review URL, and review text and

66
00:03:25,310 --> 00:03:28,945
basically converting our list of dictionaries into a DataFrame.

67
00:03:28,945 --> 00:03:34,460
Let's use df.head to print the first few rows of our DataFrame after running this code,

68
00:03:34,460 --> 00:03:36,800
and we see that the title, URL,

69
00:03:36,800 --> 00:03:39,110
and the review text columns are all populated

70
00:03:39,110 --> 00:03:43,290
correctly with the data from our text files in our directory.

